dla@athena (Don Alvarez) writes:

>Oh, how quickly they forget....

>In article <FAIGIN.94Apr8092012@solarium.aero.org> faigin@aero.org (Daniel P. Faigin) writes:
>>Most computers are virus proof; it's just PCs that are not.
>>
>>In most other systems (for example, most Unixii), the operating system runs in
>>a different mode, and application programs cannot tamper with the operating
>>systems.
>>Anything with this characteristic should be
>>immune from viruses that attack the operating system.
>>
>>Daniel

>Ummm... How about the Internet Virus of 1988, which brought
>the internet to it's knees and panic'ed the defense department?

>I can speak from personal experience that all of the unix machines
>in the building where I worked were hit and knocked out.

>Those who do not remember the past are doomed to ...
>(somewhere on an MIT gopher you can find the definitive post-mortem
>on the virus, written by Mark Eichen and Jon Rochlis, but don't
>ask me where, because I don't know).

>Now, at the risk of showing my own folly, let me suggest that
>machines which use a Harvard-architecture (as opposed to a
>Von Neuman architecture) really *are* virus proof.  

>All major desktop computers today use the Von Neuman architecture,
>where "program" memory and "data" memory live in the same space.
>This allows for self-modifying code, which I think is a prerequisite
>for virus propagation.

>By contrast, the Harvard-architecture (which I think predates the
>Von Neuman architecture) uses separate "program" and "memory"
>spaces.  If those spaces are rigidly separated then programs
>can not modify themselves or each other, preventing (I think)
>the propagation of viruses.  Many common microcontrollers use
>this type of architecture, with program memory in prom and
>data memory in ram.

A virus does not need to modify any code. It can simply place code
somewhere and then run it. No modification may need to take place. 
